<h2 class="wsite-content-title" style="text-align:center;">News and Photos<br /></h2>

<div><div style="height: 20px; overflow: hidden; width: 100%;"></div>
<hr class="styled-hr" style="width:100%;"></hr>
<div style="height: 20px; overflow: hidden; width: 100%;"></div></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:center;"><font size="5">Nationally Eminent Journal Praises<br />Delegate Ware for 2023 Legislative Victory</font><br /><br /></div>

<div class="paragraph">Delegate Lee Ware is accorded high praise in a lead report in the June edition of <em>The Atlantic Monthly </em>for his long, lonely quest to restore oversight of utility rates to the State Corporation Commission (SCC).<br /><br />George Packer, author of the piece entitled, &ldquo;The Plutocrat vs. The Monopoly&rdquo; (the plutocrat is Michael Bills of Charlottesville, founder of Clean Virginia, and the monopoly is Dominion Energy), interviewed Delegate Ware in the legislator&rsquo;s office in Powhatan Court House.&nbsp; Del. Ware, a Republican, was patron of House Bill 1604 of the 2023 General Assembly; chief co-patron was Delegate Rip Sullivan, Democrat of Fairfax-Arlington.&nbsp; With the crucial support of Governor Glenn Youngkin, the bill&mdash;one in a series that Del. Ware has proposed for more than a decade&mdash;was passed unanimously by both chambers of the legislature.&nbsp; Its effect will be to dramatically lower&mdash;or at least to limit&mdash;the cost of electricity for ratepayers.<br /><br />&ldquo;Over the years, a few lonely legislators spoke up against Dominion [for having in 2007 gained passage of a bill to limit SCC oversight of its rates],&rdquo; Mr. Packer writes.&nbsp; &ldquo;One was Lee Ware, a white-haired Republican member of the House of Delegates in rural central Virginia.<br /><br />&ldquo;The walls of Delegate Ware&rsquo;s home library are lined with works of literature, philosophy, and theology, along with portraits of Confederate generals [editor&rsquo;s note: and with an historic memento of a distinguished Union colonel].&nbsp; When I visited, Ware was reading Jacques Barzun and the letters of Flannery O&rsquo;Connor; his political models are Edmund Burke and Cicero.<br /><br />&ldquo;Ware actually read Dominion&rsquo;s bills, and for years he was the only Republican to speak and vote against them consistently.&nbsp; &lsquo;It became evident to me,&rdquo; Del. Ware explained, &ldquo;that Dominion was putting their thumb on the scale on their own behalf,&rsquo; he said, in a way that must be called &lsquo;courtly.&rsquo; &lsquo;It just over time became evident that this was unseemly,&rsquo;&rdquo; Delegate Ware commented.<br /><br />Mr. Packer explains the history of Del. Ware&rsquo;s decade-long quest to restore oversight of utility-monopolies&rsquo; rate requests to the SCC, and again refers to Delegate Ware&rsquo;s instrumental success in the 2023 Assembly:<br /><br />&ldquo;Delegate Lee Ware, the longtime Republican&hellip;spoke of &lsquo;the sense that Big Tech, Big Pharma, Big Insurance, big banks that are too big to fail&mdash;these behemoths are in control of our lives, and the ordinary citizen says, &lsquo;Who speaks for me?&rsquo;&rdquo;<br /><br />As House Bill 1604 of 2023 demonstrates, the answer is&hellip;Delegate Lee Ware.<br /></div>

<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center">
