<div class="paragraph"><font size="6" color="#2a2a2a">VEA Names Delegate Ware a 2019 "Legislative Champion"<br /></font><br /></div>

<span class='imgPusher' style='float:right;height:0px'></span><span style='display: table;width:auto;position:relative;float:right;max-width:100%;;clear:right;margin-top:0px;*margin-top:0px'><a><img src="/uploads/1/2/7/2/127232404/editor/photo-vea-champion-award-delegate-ware-vea-president-jim-livingston-12-1.jpg?1567636621" style="margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 10px; border-width:0; max-width:100%" alt="Picture" class="galleryImageBorder wsite-image" /></a><span style="display: table-caption; caption-side: bottom; font-size: 90%; margin-top: -10px; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;" class="wsite-caption"></span></span>
<div class="paragraph" style="display:block;">Teaching was Delegate Ware&rsquo;s vocation&mdash;for 32 years&mdash;and public education is among his top priorities, each and every General Assembly, indeed, each and every day of every year.&nbsp; Happily, he was able this year to contribute to one of the major initiatives of the Virginia Education Association (VEA), and the VEA has shown its gratitude by naming Delegate Ware recipient of a &ldquo;Legislative Champion Award&rdquo; for 2019.&nbsp;<br /><br />Making the presentation was VEA President Jim Livingston, left, of Prince William County.&nbsp; The presentation came at the VEA&rsquo;s Summer Training in the Reggie Smith Organization School held at the University of Richmond in mid-July.&nbsp; Del. Ware was commended for his work as Chief Co-patron of House Bill 2037, the &lsquo;Diversifying Teacher Workforce Act&rdquo; reforming licensure criteria for new teachers.&nbsp; As chairman of the House Finance Committee, Del. Ware able to ensure the bill&rsquo;s passage, according to Mr. Livingston.&nbsp;<br /><br />The VEA is "the largest and oldest professional organization serving public schools and public-school educators in the Commonwealth."</div>
